00:03:26.670 --> 00:03:30.956
So starting with a
little bit of history,

00:03:30.956 --> 00:03:34.330
the Exploratorium
was founded in 1969

00:03:34.330 --> 00:03:37.470
by Frank Oppenheimer, a
brother of Robert Oppenheimer.

00:03:37.470 --> 00:03:40.050
And they worked side by side
on the Manhattan Project.

00:03:40.050 --> 00:03:43.630
Frank was a lifelong educator
with a passion for education

00:03:43.630 --> 00:03:46.860
and had notions about
creating a way of learning

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:51.230
that was hands-on,
interactive, learner-driven

00:03:51.230 --> 00:03:53.560
and felt there was a need
to transform education

00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:55.190
as we knew it.

00:03:55.190 --> 00:03:58.700
Before the Exploratorium, if you
were to go to a science center,

00:03:58.700 --> 00:04:00.480
it was largely artifact-based.

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:03.560
It was a place that you would
see the artifacts of science

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:04.720
or the history of science.

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:06.720
So the way we think of
science centers right now

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:09.240
is a place where you put
your hands on experiments

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:12.050
and authentic phenomena
by and large didn't exist.

00:04:12.050 --> 00:04:14.440
And the Exploratorium
played a critical role

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:18.339
in creating what we now know
as the informal science center

00:04:18.339 --> 00:04:19.019
movement.

00:04:19.019 --> 00:04:21.560
Our original home was at
the Palace of Fine Arts.

00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:26.050
The famous story is in 1969, one
day they just opened the doors.

00:04:26.050 --> 00:04:30.690
People came in, and the
museum was declared open.

00:04:30.690 --> 00:04:33.770
About two years ago, we moved
to our new location, the San

00:04:33.770 --> 00:04:35.880
Francisco waterfront
on the Embarcadero.

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:38.200
It was an incredibly
transformative time

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:40.630
for the institution and
in many ways directly

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:43.210
relates to the ways in
which we started interfacing

00:04:43.210 --> 00:04:44.540
with the wider world.

00:04:44.540 --> 00:04:45.990
We're more centrally located.

00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:48.670
We started thinking more
broadly about the way

00:04:48.670 --> 00:04:52.920
in which we partner with people,
the way in which we approach

00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:55.160
content, and even
the types of content

00:04:55.160 --> 00:04:57.250
sets that we are
able to explore,

00:04:57.250 --> 00:04:59.350
not to mention the fact
that is significantly more

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:01.100
accessible for those
of you who know where

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:02.400
the Palace of Fine Art is.

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:04.360
It's out in the edge
of San Francisco

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:05.624
by the Golden Gate Bridge.

00:05:05.624 --> 00:05:07.790
I strongly suspect that a
strong portion of visitors

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:09.331
who tried to get to
the Exploratorium

00:05:09.331 --> 00:05:10.860
ended up on the
Golden Gate Bridge.

00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:12.627
And now, we're on
public transportation.

00:05:12.627 --> 00:05:14.960
We're more accessible to a
wider variety of communities,

00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:19.240
including the South
Bay and East Bay.

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:22.090
What makes the Exploratorium so
special and one of the reasons

00:05:22.090 --> 00:05:24.395
it's had the impact it
has is its approach.

00:05:24.395 --> 00:05:26.770
And I'd actually like to take
a moment to talk about some

00:05:26.770 --> 00:05:29.160
of the core elements
of our approach.

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:31.230
And the first and perhaps
the most important

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:34.085
is that we have a deep
pedagogical underpinning that

00:05:34.085 --> 00:05:36.220
is about inquiry-based learning.

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:38.960
And simply put, that means
that it's learner-driven.

00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:40.680
You form your own questions.

00:05:40.680 --> 00:05:42.080
You create your own experience.

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:43.420
You create your own pathways.

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:47.626
You create your own interest, as
opposed to somebody telling you

00:05:47.626 --> 00:05:49.250
this is the thing
that you're studying.

00:05:49.250 --> 00:05:51.291
This is the thing you're
supposed to be learning.

00:05:51.291 --> 00:05:53.539
These are the questions that
we expect you to answer.

00:05:53.539 --> 00:05:55.205
This is one of our
most famous exhibits.

00:05:55.205 --> 00:05:57.020
It's a turntable exhibit.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:59.620
And basically, it's a rotating
table with a bunch of objects

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:02.620
that you place on it and spin
and observe what happens.

00:06:02.620 --> 00:06:03.620
There is no sign.

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:06.440
There is no explicit content.

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:08.830
And yet, it's about engagement.

00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:10.260
It's about play.

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:14.170
It's about hands-on an
understanding of the universe.

00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:16.922
Should you choose, then,
to explore content,

00:06:16.922 --> 00:06:18.630
obviously there's an
awful lot of physics

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:20.260
that's going on
below the surface,

00:06:20.260 --> 00:06:22.810
enough to keep a
classroom or even

00:06:22.810 --> 00:06:28.020
a university student occupied
should you go that direction.

00:06:28.020 --> 00:06:30.140
We believe in
authentic phenomena.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:32.230
So the exhibits on the
Exploratorium floor,

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:33.180
they're not models.

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:34.460
They're not simulations.

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:35.780
They are the real phenomena.

00:06:35.780 --> 00:06:37.780
And that dates all the
way back to our founding,

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:41.840
where exhibits started off as
props, as experiments that you

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:43.430
actually get your hands on.

00:06:43.430 --> 00:06:47.250
And this is an exhibit called
water drop photography, where

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:49.910
you can time how long it
takes for a water drop

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:51.270
to fall into a cup of water.

00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:52.400
Then you take a picture.

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:55.680
And you can time where the
water droplet is in its journey

00:06:55.680 --> 00:06:57.470
when you take the picture.

00:06:57.470 --> 00:06:59.150
There's also
unexpected phenomena.

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:01.150
If you were to look inside
the droplet of water,

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:02.190
you see the lens.

00:07:02.190 --> 00:07:04.220
And you see the
upside down image.

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:07.290
Again, you start with play and
interactivity, not the lesson

00:07:07.290 --> 00:07:10.550
about optics and lenses.

00:07:10.550 --> 00:07:12.820
Art and science is
another fundamental part

00:07:12.820 --> 00:07:14.710
of the Exploratorium
core approach,

00:07:14.710 --> 00:07:18.870
that we believe that the
processes of discovery of art

00:07:18.870 --> 00:07:20.680
and science are very similar.

00:07:20.680 --> 00:07:23.060
And the beauty of
natural phenomena

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:25.190
and an artistic approach
provides a rather

00:07:25.190 --> 00:07:28.650
profound toe-hold for learners.

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:31.010
So this is a picture inside
the new Exploratorium.

00:07:31.010 --> 00:07:33.780
And the last fundamental
aspect I would touch on right

00:07:33.780 --> 00:07:39.610
now is that of accessibility and
the power of creative engines

00:07:39.610 --> 00:07:44.104
and a sense of perpetual,
constant prototyping.

00:07:44.104 --> 00:07:46.270
This is our shop, which is
very unusual for museums,

00:07:46.270 --> 00:07:48.310
is right next to our floor.

00:07:48.310 --> 00:07:52.540
There's only a short pony wall
in between visitors and machine

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:53.367
shop tools.

00:07:53.367 --> 00:07:55.200
And that was how it was
in the old building.

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:56.570
And that is how it is
in the new building.

00:07:56.570 --> 00:07:57.980
It didn't have to be that way.

00:07:57.980 --> 00:08:00.890
But we insisted that
it be so in large part

00:08:00.890 --> 00:08:03.250
to demonstrate the fact
that there is no magic.

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:07.130
Here is where the Exploratorium
and is being created.

00:08:07.130 --> 00:08:09.410
And those who are creating
it have direct access

00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:12.270
to the floor and our constantly
testing out their ideas

00:08:12.270 --> 00:08:13.000
on our floor.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.680
We don't presume to get an
exhibit right or an experience

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:19.382
